<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Endemic to the Vallegrande area in the Bolivian inter-Andean valleys where it is uncommon in open grassy scrubland on hillsides from 1900 to 2200(-2500) m.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">BOLIVIA. Santa Cruz</emphasis>
: Vallegrande area, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">I. Vargas</emphasis>
33 (NY); road to Tierras Nuevas, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">M. Nee et al.</emphasis>
37406 (NY); on descent to Piraimiri, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">J.R.I. Wood et al.</emphasis>
21743 (LPB); Vallegrande-Postrervalle, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
G.A. 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Tingidae" genus="Parada" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Parada</taxonomicName>
et al.
</emphasis>
5326 (MO, USZ).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">This appears to be a rather isolated species morphologically. The subterminal inflorescence suggests it is essentially erect or ascending in habit, as indicated by most field notes, but it is unlike most erect species in South America in its broad leaves and Andean habitat.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
